What is Node.js
Node.js is an open-source JavaScript runtime environment that allows JavaScript to run outside the browser. It is built on the V8 JavaScript engine and is mainly used to develop backend applications, APIs, and server-side programs.

Steps to Install Node.js
Step 1: Open Official Website
Open any web browser and visit the official Node.js website: https://nodejs.org/

Step 2: Download Node.js
On the website, select the LTS (Long Term Support) version and download the installer suitable for your operating system.

Step 3: Install Node.js (Windows / macOS / Linux)
Windows: Open the downloaded .msi file, click Next, accept the license agreement, keep default options, click Install, and complete the setup.

macOS: Open the downloaded .pkg file, click Continue, click Install, enter the system password, and allow the installation to complete.

Linux (Ubuntu/Debian): Open Terminal and run the following commands:

sudo apt update

sudo apt install nodejs npm

Step 4: Verify Node.js Installation
Open Command Prompt / Terminal and run:

node -v

npm -v

If version numbers are displayed, Node.js is installed successfully.

Step 5: Optional â€“ Update npm
To update npm to the latest version, run:

npm install -g npm

Step 6: Installation Completed
Node.js is now ready to use, and you can start running JavaScript files and building backend applications.

Running Node.js (File and Project)
Open Command Prompt / Terminal

Navigate to the project or file folder using cd

To run a single JavaScript file, use:

node app.js

To run a Node.js project, ensure package.json exists

Install dependencies if required:

npm install

Start the project using:

npm start

If output appears, Node.js is running successfully
